---
title: "Bayesian Workflow"
guide-section: "Concepts"
jupyter: pathmc
bread-crumbs: false
---

Bayesian modeling is iterative. You don't write a model, press "run", and accept whatever comes out. You build up confidence through a cycle of **inspection, simulation, and refinement** — before and after fitting to data.

pathmc supports this workflow directly. Every step — from inspecting priors to simulating interventions — is a method call on the same `PathModel` object.

```{dot}
//| label: fig-workflow
//| fig-cap: "The Bayesian workflow in pathmc. The inner loop (prior predictive checks) is fast and iterative. The outer loop (model revision) involves rethinking causal structure."
//| fig-width: 5.5
digraph {
  rankdir=TB
  node [shape=box, style=rounded, fontsize=12]
  edge [fontsize=10]

  specify [label="1. Build model\nmodel(spec, data)"]
  inspect [label="2. Inspect structure\ngraph(), equations()"]
  ppc [label="3. Prior predictive check\nsample_prior_predictive()"]
  plausible [label="Plausible?", shape=diamond]
  refine [label="4. Refine priors\nset_priors()"]
  sample [label="5. Fit\nfit()"]
  check [label="6. Posterior checks\nsummary(), predict()"]
  goodfit [label="Good fit?", shape=diamond]
  revise [label="Revise model", style="rounded,dashed"]
  causal [label="7. Causal queries\nate(), do(), prob()"]

  specify -> inspect
  inspect -> ppc
  ppc -> plausible
  plausible -> refine [label="No"]
  refine -> ppc
  plausible -> sample [label="Yes"]
  sample -> check
  check -> goodfit
  goodfit -> revise [label="No"]
  revise -> specify
  goodfit -> causal [label="Yes"]
}
```

Each step is one or two method calls. We walk through the full cycle below on a simple mediation model.


## Simulate data

We use synthetic data with known coefficients so we can verify recovery at each stage.

::: {#7dfe41fb .cell execution_count=1}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

rng = np.random.default_rng(42)
n = 500

X = rng.normal(size=n)
M = 0.5 * X + rng.normal(scale=0.3, size=n)
Y = 0.8 * M + 0.3 * X + rng.normal(scale=0.3, size=n)

df = pd.DataFrame({"X": X, "M": M, "Y": Y})
```
:::


True values: $a = 0.5$, $b = 0.8$, $c = 0.3$.


## 1. Build the model

Write causal assumptions as structural equations. `model()` compiles the spec and data into a `PathModel` — ready for inspection — without running MCMC.

::: {#9225ff1c .cell execution_count=2}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import pathmc
from pathmc import Prior

spec = """
M ~ a*X
Y ~ b*M + c*X
indirect := a*b
"""

model = pathmc.model(spec, data=df)
```
:::


## 2. Inspect structure

Before spending any compute on sampling, verify that the model encodes what you intend.

::: {#1396a7b0 .cell execution_count=3}
``` {.python .cell-code}
model.graph()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3}
![](bayesian-workflow_files/figure-html/cell-4-output-1.svg){}
:::
:::


::: {#5aa939ad .cell execution_count=4}
``` {.python .cell-code}
model.equations()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown execution_count=4}
$$
\begin{aligned}
\beta_{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=10) \\
\sigma_{M} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=1) \\
\beta_{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=10) \\
\sigma_{Y} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=1)
\\[6pt]
\mu_{M} &= \beta_{0,\,M} + a \cdot \mathrm{X} \\
\mathrm{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{M},\, \sigma_{M}) \\
\mu_{Y} &= \beta_{0,\,Y} + b \cdot \mathrm{M} + c \cdot \mathrm{X} \\
\mathrm{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{Y},\, \sigma_{Y}) \\
indirect &\equiv a \cdot b
\end{aligned}
$$
:::
:::


`equations()` shows the structural equations and the prior distribution assigned to every parameter, including defaults you may not have thought about. The defaults are deliberately vague: `Normal(0, 10)` for regression coefficients and `HalfNormal(1)` for residual scales. These work out of the box, but domain knowledge almost always lets you do better.


## 3. Prior predictive check

A prior predictive check asks: *if we generated data from our priors (without seeing real data), would it look remotely plausible?*

::: {#9144ec76 .cell execution_count=5}
``` {.python .cell-code}
ppc_default = model.sample_prior_predictive(draws=500, random_seed=42)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
Sampling: [M, Y, beta_M, beta_Y, sigma_M, sigma_Y]
```
:::
:::


::: {#cell-fig-ppc-default .cell execution_count=6}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true"}
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import arviz as az

FIG_WIDTH = 7
FIG_HEIGHT = 3.5
COLOR_DEFAULT = "#1b9e77"
COLOR_CUSTOM = "#d95f02"

y_prior = ppc_default.prior["Y"].values.flatten()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(FIG_WIDTH, FIG_HEIGHT))
x_kde, y_kde, _ = az.kde(y_prior)
ax.plot(x_kde, y_kde, color=COLOR_DEFAULT, lw=2, label="Prior predictive (defaults)")
ax.fill_between(x_kde, y_kde, alpha=0.6, color=COLOR_DEFAULT)
ax.axvline(
    df["Y"].mean(),
    color="black",
    linestyle="--",
    linewidth=1.5,
    label=f"Observed mean = {df['Y'].mean():.2f}",
)
ax.set_xlabel("Y")
ax.set_ylabel("Density")
ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Prior predictive distribution of Y under default priors. The tails extend well beyond the observed data range, indicating the model considers extreme outcomes plausible.](bayesian-workflow_files/figure-html/fig-ppc-default-output-1.png){#fig-ppc-default width=660 height=326}
:::
:::


The default priors generate Y values spanning a huge range. For this dataset, where Y lives roughly in $[-2, 2]$, coefficients of $\pm 10$ are implausible. We can do better.


## 4. Refine priors

`set_priors()` merges overrides into the current configuration and recompiles. Only the parameters you specify change.

::: {#0c604a51 .cell execution_count=7}
``` {.python .cell-code}
model.set_priors({
    "beta_M": Prior("Normal", mu=0, sigma=2),
    "beta_Y": Prior("Normal", mu=0, sigma=2),
    "sigma_M": Prior("HalfNormal", sigma=0.5),
    "sigma_Y": Prior("HalfNormal", sigma=0.5),
})

model.equations()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display .cell-output-markdown execution_count=7}
$$
\begin{aligned}
\beta_{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=2) \\
\sigma_{M} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=0.5) \\
\beta_{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(mu=0,\, sigma=2) \\
\sigma_{Y} &\sim \text{HalfNormal}(sigma=0.5)
\\[6pt]
\mu_{M} &= \beta_{0,\,M} + a \cdot \mathrm{X} \\
\mathrm{M} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{M},\, \sigma_{M}) \\
\mu_{Y} &= \beta_{0,\,Y} + b \cdot \mathrm{M} + c \cdot \mathrm{X} \\
\mathrm{Y} &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu_{Y},\, \sigma_{Y}) \\
indirect &\equiv a \cdot b
\end{aligned}
$$
:::
:::


Now re-check: do the refined priors generate plausible data?

::: {#f8fa7e35 .cell execution_count=8}
``` {.python .cell-code}
ppc_custom = model.sample_prior_predictive(draws=500, random_seed=42)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
Sampling: [M, Y, beta_M, beta_Y, sigma_M, sigma_Y]
```
:::
:::


::: {#cell-fig-ppc-comparison .cell execution_count=9}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true"}
y_default = ppc_default.prior["Y"].values.flatten()
y_custom = ppc_custom.prior["Y"].values.flatten()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(FIG_WIDTH, FIG_HEIGHT))
x_kde, y_kde, _ = az.kde(y_default)
ax.plot(x_kde, y_kde, color=COLOR_DEFAULT, lw=2, label="Default priors")
ax.fill_between(x_kde, y_kde, alpha=0.45, color=COLOR_DEFAULT)
x_kde, y_kde, _ = az.kde(y_custom)
ax.plot(x_kde, y_kde, color=COLOR_CUSTOM, lw=2, label="Refined priors")
ax.fill_between(x_kde, y_kde, alpha=0.55, color=COLOR_CUSTOM)
ax.axvline(
    df["Y"].mean(),
    color="black",
    linestyle="--",
    linewidth=1.5,
    label=f"Observed mean = {df['Y'].mean():.2f}",
)
ax.set_xlabel("Y")
ax.set_ylabel("Density")
ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Prior predictive distributions under default (green) and refined (orange) priors. The refined priors concentrate mass in the plausible range.](bayesian-workflow_files/figure-html/fig-ppc-comparison-output-1.png){#fig-ppc-comparison width=660 height=326}
:::
:::


The refined priors concentrate probability mass in the plausible range — much better. The model still allows coefficients up to $\pm 4$--$6$ (generous), but no longer considers coefficients of 10 or 20 as likely.

::: {.callout-tip}
## This loop is cheap

`sample_prior_predictive()` draws from priors without MCMC — it runs in seconds. Iterate as many times as needed before committing to a full posterior fit.
:::


## 5. Fit

With priors that generate plausible data, run MCMC.

::: {#ca2e3a23 .cell execution_count=10}
``` {.python .cell-code}
model.fit(draws=500, tune=500, chains=4, random_seed=42)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
NUTS[nutpie]: [beta_Y, sigma_M, beta_M, sigma_Y]
```
:::

